<p class="center small">✪  The First Global Frontier  ✪</p>

<p>
  By the time John Wayne Lee was born, his ancestry had already crossed an ocean, multiple
  colonial regimes, a revolution, westward migrations, civil wars, economic depressions,
  and the massive social changes of the twentieth century. He did not arrive in a vacuum.
  He arrived as the living synthesis of all the lines described in the previous chapters.
</p>

<p>
  From his father’s side, John inherited the quiet dignity and leadership instincts
  associated with the Lee–Ludwell–Harrison and Brittain–Rhyne lines. There is a certain
  internal structure to these traits: a sense of responsibility, a seriousness about
  commitments, and an ability to hold positions of trust. These qualities would later
  express themselves in John’s career in public service and federal leadership.
</p>

<p>
  From his mother’s side, he inherited the warmth, resilience, and deep human empathy of
  the Myrick, Rogers, Wilder, and related families. In them, the measure of a person was
  found less in title and more in whether they would show up, help, and endure. This
  maternal inheritance would shape John’s capacity to connect with people, to care, and to
  keep going through personal and professional trials.
</p>

<p>
  As a young adult and later, John’s life reflected a pattern that had been present in his
  ancestry for centuries: movement toward new frontiers. But instead of moving from
  Virginia to Tennessee or from Arkansas to Oklahoma, John crossed national borders and
  cultural boundaries. His service as a Peace Corps Volunteer in Ostional, Costa Rica, was
  a turning point. There, he stepped into a role that combined leadership, service,
  cross-cultural understanding, and personal courage—all qualities rooted deeply in his
  family history, but expressed in a global setting his ancestors could never have
  imagined.
</p>

